About
Better known as Big Ben (it's actually the name of the Great Bell!), this iconic clock tower which stands at the Houses of Parliament is officially called the Elizabeth Tower, named in honor of Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee. When the Elizabeth Tower is open for tours, you can climb up the tower and admire the clock and bell up close. But fret not, you can still learn about its history and admire its ornate golden facade on a tour of London or the Houses of Parliament.
Duration: < 1 hour

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Westminster
If you only had an afternoon to experience London on a grand scale, Westminster would be a wise place to start. The ornate Houses of Parliament and Westminster Abbey sit adjacent at a corner of Parliament Square, and a short stroll along The Mall leads to Buckingham Palace. Trafalgar Square and Nelson's Column are just up the road as well. As captivating as the architecture is, the wonders of Mother Nature are highlights of the area too. St James's Park (arguably London's loveliest), the expansive Green Park, and pedestrian friendly tree lined paths along the river showcase the exquisite manicure provided by English gardeners. Just beyond the landmarks and the gorgeous outdoor spaces, quiet residential squares and age old local pubs offer a more subdued take on this global seat of power in the heart of London.
How to get there
  • Embankment 10 min walk
  • Waterloo 10 min walk

London, UK186 contributions
My favourite tour in London
Oct 2024 Solo
What a fabulous tour!
You can only book to actually walk up Elizabeth Tower and see the big ben bell via the uk parliament website.
The closest tube station is Westminster and then it's a short walk to the entrance.

Wear comfortable shoes as there are 334 steps but the tour guide breaks this down into chunks so you stop and get given some history. Our tour guide was Melissa and she was fantastic!

As well as all of the history, the tour includes the mechanism room, walking at the back of all the clock faces and standing by the bells as they strike (ear plugs are provided).

You can also view Westminster hall and the beautiful reception area. If it's not too busy you can also go into the viewing gallery of parliament.

Try and book at time were you can see the bell strike more than once. I had a 11.45 tour but by the time we got to the bells we got the 1pm strike so only once.

Toilets, cafe, water font and souvenir shop are available at the start and end of the tour.

Camera use is restricted so you can only take pictures in the hall for health and safety reasons.

Exploring Big Ben: A Timeless London Icon
Oct 2024 Solo
Big Ben, officially known as the Great Bell of the clock at the north end of the Palace of Westminster, is one of London's most recognizable landmarks. Heres a guide to make the most of your visit to this iconic site.

Best Time to Visit:
Plan your visit during the day for the best views and photos. The area around Big Ben can get quite busy, so early mornings or late afternoons are ideal for a more relaxed experience. The chimes of the clock can be heard every 15 minutes, adding to the charm of your visit.

Getting There:
Big Ben is easily accessible by public transport. The nearest tube stations are Westminster, St. James's Park, and Embankment. If you prefer a scenic route, consider a walk along the Thames, which offers beautiful views of the river and the city skyline.

What to See:
While the interior of the clock tower is currently closed to the public due to ongoing restoration work, the exterior still provides a stunning backdrop for photos. Take a moment to admire the Gothic architecture and the intricate details of the clock face. The nearby Houses of Parliament and Westminster Abbey are also must-see attractions, rich in history and architectural beauty.

Nearby Attractions:
Extend your visit by exploring the surrounding area. The Houses of Parliament offer guided tours, providing insight into the UKs political history. Westminster Abbey, just a short walk away, is a treasure trove of royal and historical significance. For a different perspective, take a boat tour on the Thames, which offers a unique view of Big Ben and other riverside landmarks.

Tips for Your Visit:
Check the official website for any updates on the restoration work and potential reopening dates.
Bring a camera to capture the impressive views and the historic surroundings.
Wear comfortable shoes, as theres plenty to see and explore in the area.
Using the C0DE RC777E in Trainpal can save a lot of money for you.

Big Ben is more than just a clock; its a symbol of Londons enduring heritage. Whether youre a history buff or simply looking to soak in the citys atmosphere, a visit to Big Ben is an essential part of any London itinerary.
Written October 15, 2024
